About
The quirky colorful mosaics and undulating curves of Park GÃ¼ell are a signature of the legendary Catalan architect Antoni Gaudi, who designed many of the features in this park. Officially opened in 1926 and initially planned as a district for the rich, it is now one of the city's most popular attractions and a great representation of Catalan modernism. The entrance with two fairytale-like houses and the iconic salamander fountain are the most busy. Tickets are required to enter the park.
Duration: 2-3 hours

Neighborhood: Gracia
Gracia literally stands out from the pack. It used to be an independent town until late into the 19th century. Though itâs just a short commute away from the center, a visit here feels like youâre in a whole different city. The bohemian vibe has drawn many international artists to this area, resulting in a wide selection of galleries, live music and artsy boutique stores. The nightlife is centered around the vibrant Graciaâs plaÃ§as, where young and old gather to enjoy a drink outside. Carrer de Verdi, its main street, offers affordable restaurants and a movie theater that screens new as well as classic films in their original language. However Gracia's greatest treasure lies just up the hill at Guell Park, where Antoni Gaudi's vibrant and revolutionary art sculptures stand atop unequaled views of Barcelona.

Aimless wandering in Park Guell
Nov 2024 â¢ Friends
Possibly the inspiration for Edward Munchâs Scream!

Entered the park at the upper entrance to be greeted by a QR code to scan for a map of the park. No signal up there so tried the park wifi which due to the strength and traffic estimated a 1 hour download speed.

We followed fellow tourist zombies round the park up and down unmarked trails, steep stairs and hills.. there is very little signage and no explanation. A park attendant got really defensive when my sister asked for a map, suggesting she was out to kill the planet. No, laminate or make a hard copy that visitors can take a photo of please. Many of the thousands of poor-average reviews mention a lack of signage but is there change for a better visitor experience? Sadly not.

When we got down to the bottom (where all the action was) there was a numbered map which would have been good to follow except you couldnât go from point 2 to point 3 and 4 where the mosaic lizard is, you had to walk away back up the hill to point 13 where there are no signs to point you in the direction of this desired area.

You can actually see the Gaudi buildings from outside the main entrance and take a photo from there.

There are nice views over the city, 2 viaduct bridges and the park has shade from the greenery. There are however other lovely free parks in Barcelona like Ciutadella Park

Our package included the Gaudi Experience which is separate and very well done. ( But there are no sign posts to tell you where it is! )

For a 5 star experience go to Casa BatllÃ³ or Sagrada which are both stunning and well organised.

Under -Guell-ming
Oct 2024 â¢ Couples
Park Guell is located on the edge of town and up a hill. So itâs best to arrive by taxi. Purchase tickets well ahead of time and make sure itâs from the official website. There is more than one entrance but the main entrance on Carrer dâOlot is probably the best place to begin. We hiked in a counter-clockwise route but itâs not necessary. You can wander in any direction and see everything at your own pace. There is no place in the park to purchase food or drink, so if you think youâll need it, pack some of your own. There is a guided tour available, but I did not use a guide because I like to go at my own pace and not herded around in large groups. Spend at minimum one hour exploring. But remember it is a park. And if you feel like sitting in one place for 30 minutes enjoying the views, or visiting the Gaudi House Museum (an additional ticket purchase), then you could spend 3 hours here. For me, Parc Guell was a little underwhelming. If you have the time, then itâs not a bad place to visit. But if your time is limited, there are other attractions in Barcelona that I would place higher in priority.
